Ruthie Bolton scored 14 of her 21
points in the second half Tuesday night, leading the Sacramento
Monarchs to a 74-65 victory over the Indiana Fever.
article.headline: Sacramento beats Indiana for fifth consecutive victory
article.linkText: Monarchs continue to play the role of spoiler
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Ruthie Bolton scored 14 of her 21
points in the second half Tuesday night, leading the Sacramento
Monarchs to a 74-65 victory over the Indiana Fever.

	   The Monarchs (9-16), who closed on an 11-2 run, won their fifth
in a row and seventh in nine games. Four Sacramento players scored
in double figures.

	   ''Our record right now doesn't reflect how well we're playing,''
Bolton said.

	   Tamika Catchings had 24 points, 11 rebounds and five assists for
Indiana (10-15), which lost its second consecutive game and is
fighting for the fourth and final playoff berth in the Eastern
Conference.

	   ''I thought we gave a great effort, but we just couldn't finish
it out,'' Catchings said. ''When you have four players in doubles
figures it makes it really tough to win.''

	   Bolton made a 3-pointer with 4:24 remaining, putting the
Monarchs ahead for good at 66-63. Yolanda Griffith followed with
consecutive baskets, the second one on a rebound, giving Sacramento
a 70-63 lead with 56 seconds left.

	   ''Ruthie brings a spark to the team, she hit critical shots as
well as being a matchup problem for Indiana,'' Sacramento coach
Maura McHugh said. ''These last five games have brought a renewed
confidence to this team.''

	   Tangela Smith scored 16 points for Sacramento, Kedra
Holland-Corn had 15, and Ticha Penicheiro added 13 assists.

	   Olympia Scott-Richardson had 15 points and eight rebounds before
fouling out. Nikki McCray added 10 points for the Fever.

	   Trailing 36-35 at intermission, Indiana scored the first eight
points of the second half. Despite going nearly seven minutes
without a second-half rebound, the Monarchs tied it 49-49 on a
three-point play by Yolanda Griffith.
